definition: "Galectin-3 is a carbohydrate-binding protein (lectin) produced primarily by activated macrophages and expressed in multiple tissues throughout the body. It plays a central role in fibrosis — the pathological replacement of functional tissue with collagen-rich scar tissue — by activating fibroblasts, stimulating collagen production, and promoting macrophage infiltration into damaged tissues. In cardiovascular biology, galectin-3 is produced by cardiac macrophages in response to myocardial stress and injury, where it drives the fibrotic remodeling that transforms functional heart muscle into stiff, non-contractile scar tissue — the cellular basis of heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF) and the progression of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF). Galectin-3 also drives fibrosis in the kidneys, liver, and lungs."
why_it_matters: "Galectin-3 is FDA-cleared as a prognostic biomarker for heart failure — it predicts progression, hospitalization, and mortality in heart failure patients more powerfully than BNP or NT-proBNP in certain contexts. But its significance extends well beyond established heart failure: elevated galectin-3 in the general population without diagnosed heart disease predicts incident heart failure, cardiovascular events, and all-cause mortality in prospective cohort studies. The biological insight is that galectin-3 reflects the cumulative fibrotic burden in vital organs — a form of organ aging that is not captured by conventional biomarkers. As hearts, kidneys, and livers accumulate fibrosis with age, their functional reserve declines. Galectin-3 provides a window into this fibrotic aging process before it produces measurable organ dysfunction."

